  "prompt": "Is it true that money laundering is illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every jurisdiction around the world. **Money laundering** is the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by transferring it through a complex sequence of banking or commercial transactions, to make it appear as though it came from legitimate sources.\n\nLaws against money laundering are in place to combat organized crime, corruption, tax evasion, and other illegal activities that generate illicit funds. Countries have established stringent regulations and enforcement mechanisms to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities. Penalties for money laundering can include significant fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\nFor example:\n- In the **United States**, money laundering is a federal crime under the **Bank Secrecy Act (1970)**, the **Money Laundering Control Act (1986)**, and other related laws.\n- In the **European Union**, the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives** (AMLD) set strict requirements for financial institutions and businesses to prevent and report suspicious activities.\n- Globally, organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** work to set international standards and promote effective implementation of measures to combat money laundering.\n\nEngaging in money laundering is a serious criminal offense, and individuals or entities involved can face severe legal consequences.",
